SIMPLE: stout
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stout
<hw>Stout</hw> <pr>(stout)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos>
<amorph>[<pos>Compar.</pos> <adjf>Stouter</adjf>
<pr>(stout"⟦etil⟧r)</pr>; <pos>superl.</pos>
<adjf>Stoutest</adjf>.]</amorph> <ety>[D. <ets>stout</ets> bold (or OF.
<ets>estout</ets> bold, proud, of Teutonic origin); akin to AS.
<ets>stolt</ets>, G. <ets>stolz</ets>, and perh. to E.
<ets>stilt</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Strong; lusty; vigorous;
robust; sinewy; muscular; hence, firm; resolute; dauntless.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With hearts stern and <qex>stout</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>stouter</qex> champion never handled sword.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He lost the character of a bold, <qex>stout</qex>, magnanimous
man.</q> <rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The lords all stand⟦br⟧
To clear their cause, most resolutely <qex>stout</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Daniel.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Proud; haughty; arrogant; hard.</def>
<mark>[Archaic]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Your words have been <qex>stout</qex> against me.</q>
<rj><qau>Mal. iii. 13.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Commonly . . . they that be rich are lofty and
<qex>stout</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Latimer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Firm; tough; materially strong; enduring; <as>as, a
<ex>stout</ex> vessel, stick, string, or cloth</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Large; bulky; corpulent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Stout</er>, <er>Corpulent</er>,
<er>Portly</er>.</syn> <usage> <xex>Corpulent</xex> has reference simply
to a superabundance or excess of flesh. <xex>Portly</xex> implies a kind
of stoutness or corpulence which gives a dignified or imposing
appearance. <xex>Stout</xex>, in our early writers (as in the English
Bible), was used chiefly or wholly in the sense of <xex>strong</xex> or
<xex>bold</xex>; <as>as, a <ex>stout</ex> champion; a <ex>stout</ex>
heart; a <ex>stout</ex> resistance, etc.</as> At a later period it was
used for <xex>thickset</xex> or <xex>bulky</xex>, and more recently,
especially in England, the idea has been carried still further, so that
Taylor says in his Synonyms: ⟦ldquo⟧The <xex>stout</xex> man has the
proportions of an ox; he is corpulent, fat, and fleshy in relation to
his size.⟦rdquo⟧ In America, <xex>stout</xex> is still commonly used in
the original sense of <xex>strong</xex> as, a <xex>stout</xex> boy; a
<xex>stout</xex> pole.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>stout</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: stout
<hw>stout</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A strong, dark malt brew having a
higher percentage of hops than porter; strong porter; a popular variety
sold in the U. S. is <stype>Guinness' stout</stype>.</def>
<rj><au>Swift.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stout-hearted</ent>⟦br⟧
